# Agent MCP Tools

This project exposes a set of read-only MCP tools for AI agent use via the
`/agent-mcp` endpoint. Access is controlled by a server-admin key (no user
tokens; set `AGENT_MCP_KEY` on the server). Use these tools proactively to
ground your answers in real data rather than assumptions. The tools are safe to
call frequently; they have no write access to the database.

Enable only what you want: every tool is individually gated by the operator via
`config('agent-mcp.tools.<name>')`. Sensitive tools are off by default and must
be explicitly enabled.

## Tool Usage Table

### Core tools

| Tool | When to use | Notes | Default state |
|------|-------------|-------|---------------|
| `db_schema` | **BEFORE writing any query**, call this to discover table names, column types, indexes, and foreign keys. Also call when you encounter an unknown table or column. | Read-only schema introspection. Call with no arguments for the full table list; pass a `table` argument for column-level detail. | On |
| `db_query` | For structured reads where you know the table and filter conditions (find by id, filter by a column, count rows). Use this for well-defined lookups. | Builds parameterized queries via the query builder. Safer than raw SQL for routine reads. | On |
| `db_raw_select` | For ad-hoc or complex SELECT queries: JOINs across multiple tables, subqueries, aggregations, window functions. Always write a valid SELECT statement. | Accepts any valid SELECT. The package enforces a SELECT-only grammar guard and auto-applies a row limit. | On |
| `read_logs` | **On any 500, exception, failed job, or unexpected behavior, call this IMMEDIATELY** before attempting a fix. Log context is often the fastest path to the root cause. | Returns recent lines from the application log channel. Control volume with `lines`, and narrow by `level` (error, warning, info, debug). | On |
| `run_artisan` | Only when the operator has explicitly enabled this tool and configured an allowlist of permitted commands. Do NOT assume it is available; check first. | Disabled by default. Runs only exact commands from the operator-configured allowlist. No wildcard or arbitrary commands accepted. | Off (opt-in) |

### Queue tools

| Tool | When to use | Notes | Default state |
|------|-------------|-------|---------------|
| `queue_backlog` | When a user reports slow or missing background processing, check queue depth first before digging into code. | Returns pending job counts per connection and queue. Sync driver returns `{note:N/A}`. | On |
| `queue_failed_jobs` | When investigating failed background jobs: counts by queue/connection, or per-job details with exception summary. | Emits job class, exception first line, and `failed_at`. Raw job payload is never returned. | On |
| `horizon_status` | When the application uses Laravel Horizon and you need workload, metrics, or supervisor state. | Returns `{available:false}` when Horizon is not installed. Horizon detect-then-use. | On (availability-gated) |

### Database health tools

| Tool | When to use | Notes | Default state |
|------|-------------|-------|---------------|
| `db_index_health` | When investigating slow queries or reporting on index coverage. Optional `table` argument to scope. | PG adds unused-index detection and seq-scan advisory. MySQL uses `information_schema`. SQLite uses `pragma_index_list`. | On |
| `db_missing_fk_indexes` | When investigating foreign-key query performance or data-integrity patterns. | PG and MySQL results are definitive. SQLite result is heuristic (labelled). | On |
| `db_table_sizes` | When investigating disk usage, table bloat, or dead-tuple buildup. | PG includes dead-tuple percentage. MySQL sizes are estimates. SQLite degrades gracefully when `dbstat` is absent. | On |
| `migrations_status` | When verifying which migrations have run and in which batch. | Reports ran migrations and batch numbers. Pending detection (filesystem scan) is not performed. | On |
| `db_slow_queries` | When investigating slow query patterns. Requires `pg_stat_statements` (PG) or `performance_schema` (MySQL). | Returns `{available:false}` when the required extension or schema is absent. Results depend on privilege level. | Off (operator opt-in) |
| `db_active_locks` | When investigating lock contention, blocked queries, or deadlock symptoms. | Point-in-time snapshot. PG requires `pg_monitor` for full visibility; partial results are labelled. Returns `{available:false}` on SQLite. | Off (operator opt-in) |

### Cache tools

| Tool | When to use | Notes | Default state |
|------|-------------|-------|---------------|
| `cache_status` | When investigating cache health, optimization state, or session/cache overlap risk. | Reports all configured stores, config/routes/events cached state, opcache summary, and `session_overlap_risk`. | On |
| `cache_inspect` | When checking whether a specific cache key exists, its TTL, or its value type. | Metadata (exists, TTL, type) by default. Raw value requires `cache.allow_value_read=true` AND the key passing the block-list. | On (raw value gated) |
| `cache_keys` | When auditing what keys are stored in the cache. Use sparingly. | Database and Redis drivers only. Redis uses SCAN (never KEYS). Session-prefix keys are excluded to prevent session ID leakage. | Off (operator opt-in) |

### App introspection tools

| Tool | When to use | Notes | Default state |
|------|-------------|-------|---------------|
| `list_routes` | When mapping the application's API surface, finding a route by method/prefix/middleware, or auditing middleware coverage. | Filters: `method`, `uri_prefix`, `name_pattern`, `middleware`, `exclude_middleware`. Middleware names only; no signed-route secrets. | On |
| `inspect_route` | When you need the full detail of a single route by name or URI. | Same shape as `list_routes` plus defaults. | On |
| `app_about` | When you need a quick snapshot of the application environment, versions, cache state, or loaded extensions. | Mirrors `php artisan about`. Optional `sections` argument. | On |
| `schedule_list` | When investigating scheduled task definitions, next-run times, or overlap/single-server flags. | Includes cron expression, next-run timestamp, and all scheduling flags. | On |
| `event_list` | When mapping event/listener wiring or checking whether a listener queues or broadcasts. | Lists all registered listeners including wildcards. Classifies string, Closure, and `[class, method]` shapes. | On |
| `storage_info` | When inspecting disk configuration or symlink state. | Credentials (`key/secret/password/token`) are stripped from disk configs. Root paths are reported as-is (mild sensitivity). | On |
| `env_keys` | When you need to know which environment variables are set in the running process. | Returns key names only. Values are never returned. | On |
| `config_inspect` | When the agent needs to audit config structure or verify a specific non-sensitive config value. Enable with care. | Key tree with types by default. Values require `reveal_values=true` AND the dot-path in `safe_list` AND not matched by the block-list. Block-list always wins. | Off (operator opt-in) |

## Proactive Use

- Call `db_schema` at the start of any session that involves database work, not just
  when you hit an error. Knowing the schema up front prevents incorrect queries.
- Call `read_logs` proactively when a user reports unexpected behavior, even if they
  have not seen a 500 explicitly. Warnings and deprecations in the logs often
  explain subtle breakage.
- Prefer `db_query` over `db_raw_select` for simple lookups; use `db_raw_select`
  only when the query builder cannot express the logic.
- Do NOT attempt to infer schema from model code or migration files alone; the live
  database may differ. Always confirm with `db_schema`.
- For queue issues, reach for `queue_backlog` first to see depth, then
  `queue_failed_jobs` for error details. Use `horizon_status` when Horizon is
  deployed.
- For slow-query investigations, use `db_slow_queries` (if enabled) to find the
  worst offenders, then `db_index_health` and `db_missing_fk_indexes` to find
  structural causes.
- For cache investigations, start with `cache_status` (always on) before reaching
  for `cache_inspect` or `cache_keys`.
- `config_inspect`, `db_slow_queries`, `db_active_locks`, and `cache_keys` are off
  by default. Do not assume they are available; treat a denial as expected.

## CLI alternative (no MCP server)

When the agent-mcp MCP server is not registered, you can call the same read-only tools
from the shell with artisan (use the project's artisan form, for example
`vendor/bin/sail artisan` for Sail):

- `php artisan agent-mcp:tools` lists the available tools (`--all` includes disabled ones).
- `php artisan agent-mcp:schema <tool>` shows a tool's input schema.
- `php artisan agent-mcp:call <tool> '<json>'` invokes a tool (JSON args positionally or on
  STDIN); the result prints to stdout, the exit code is non-zero on error.

Use the CLI for one-off calls, scripts, or CI; register the MCP server for persistent
interactive use. Sensitive tools require `--allow-tty` to print to a terminal.
